'''Frederic Slater''' (c1880- 10 March 1947<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18006389 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=12 March 1947 |accessdate=22 January 2015 |page=24 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>) was an Australian journalist, poet, researcher and "authority on aboriginal folk lore".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article160503047 |title=AN ABORIGINAL SCULPTRESS. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Mail]] |date=3 March 1937 |accessdate=22 January 2015 |page=43 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

In the 1930s, Slater was founder and president of the short-lived Australian Archaeological and Education Research Society, also known as the Australian Archaeological Society. He married Katherine Elizabeth Plowman, who survived him and was executor of his will.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18014319 |title=Advertising. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=20 March 1947 |accessdate=20 March 2015 |page=17 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> They had one son, Ederic Charles James Sutherland Slater, born in January 1923.

Slater studied Aboriginal place names and archaeological sites and provided information on Aboriginal languages including, for example, the meaning of [[Canberra]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article15424246 |title=TO THE EDITOR OF THE HERALD. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=2 June 1913 |accessdate=8 September 2015 |page=11 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}
</ref> and [[Queanbeyan]].<ref>[http://www.canberratimes.com.au/act-news/going-with-the-flow-of-history-20121227-2bxty.html Ian Warden, 'Going with the flow of history'], ''Canberra Times'' 28 December 2012</ref> However, his best known contribution, which has been described as [[pseudoarchaeology]],<ref>[https://secretvisitors.wordpress.com/ What is the Kariong Hieroglyphs site? The Secret Visitors Project]</ref> is the claim that Australian Aborigianes came from Egypt, based on carvings at Devil's Rock, [[Wollombi]], in the [[Royal National Park]], [[Brunswick Heads]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article30051046 |title=Discovery Of Aborigines' Religious Mound. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=29 July 1939 |accessdate=22 January 2015 |page=22 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and other locations. In an address at Sydney, to the [[Anthropological Society of New South Wales]]. he claimed the carvings were especially significant ''...totems, symbols and ideographs, which show that the ancestors of original Australians migrated from Egypt in the late paleolithic and the neolithic ages''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17485120 |title=NATIONAL PARK ROCK CARVINGS. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=18 August 1938 |accessdate=22 January 2015 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/27137194/The Ogden Standard-Examiner » 1937 » May » 9 May 1937, Sun » Page 2]</ref>

Slater's observations and theories have been supported in recent years by other 'pseudoarchaeologists' such as [[Steven Strong]],<ref>Gojak, D. 2017, 'the Resurrection of Frederick Slater: Tales of a Pseudo-archaeologist in the 1930s and 2010s, in ''Defining the Fringe of Contemporary Australian Archaeology, Pyramidiots, Paranoia and the Paradormal'', ed Darran Jordan & Rocco Bosco, Cambridge Scholars, 2017</ref> and in 2017 the mound south of Brunswick Heads was nominated local heritage about which Salter wrote in 1939 "ABORIGINES WORSHIP MOUND-A mound 35ft. long and 15ft. high, which has been discovered about three miles from Brunswick Heads, is believed to have been an aborigines' religious mound, which was a centre of worship for aborigines from all parts of Australia before the coming of the white race.  Access to the mound is gained by a sloping pathway on one side. It appears to have been untouched for a great many years.  The president of the Archaeological Society of Australia (Mr. Frederick Slater) has deciphered many of the carvings on the sandstone, which must have been brought a considerable distance. There is none of it in the district. Another such mound is known to exist in North Australia. A Fraser Island aborigine when told of the discovery said that his tribe had been searching for the mound for years. Mr. Slater said that the attitude of silence of the aborigine after saying that was similar to that shown by other aborigines since they first came In contact with white men" (Daily Advertiser [Wagga Wagga], Wednesday 2 August 1939, page 4 http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/145374467 )<ref>[http://theedgeofreality.proboards.com/thread/3964/australias-stonehenge Steven Strong, Australia’s Stonehenge: the History of an Ancient Stone Arrangement, 16 September 2013]</ref><ref>[http://forgottenorigin.com/5-australias-stonehenge-frederic-slaters-legacy Australia’s Stonehenge: Frederic Slater’s Legacy By Steven & Evan Strong]</ref>

